%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64c520a7048ff200190d8d35%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22431%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EFruit%20fly%2C%20Drosophila%20mercatorum%3Cp%3EJose%20Casal%20and%20Peter%20Lawrence%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EA%20group%20of%20researchers%20was%20able%20to%20successfully%20engineer%20%26quot%3Bvirgin%20birth%26quot%3B%20in%20fruit%20flies.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EAsexual%20reproduction%2C%20or%20parthenogenesis%2C%20is%20common%20in%20nature%2C%20but%20had%20never%20been%20engineered.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20research%20establishes%20a%20genetic%20basis%20for%20asexual%20reproduction%2C%20and%20could%20help%20with%20pest%20control.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EScientists%20say%20they%20have%20created%20%26quot%3Bvirgin%20births%26quot%3B%20in%20female%20fruit%20flies%20for%20the%20first%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EResearchers%20were%20able%20to%20identify%20a%20gene%20that%20allowed%20the%20insects%20to%20reproduce%20without%20sperm%20from%20a%20father.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe're%20the%20first%20to%20show%20that%20you%20can%20engineer%20virgin%20births%20to%20happen%20in%20an%20animal%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Dr.%20Alexis%20Sperling%2C%20a%20researcher%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Cambridge%20who%20was%20involved%20in%20the%20study.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20was%20very%20exciting%20to%20see%20a%20virgin%20fly%20produce%20an%20embryo%20able%20to%20develop%20to%20adulthood%2C%20and%20then%20repeat%20the%20process.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3ESwitching%20'on'%20the%20right%20genes%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EVirgin%20births%2C%20known%20as%20facultative%20parthenogenesis%2C%20have%20been%20seen%20before%20in%20bees%2C%20ants%2C%20lizards%2C%20snakes%2C%20fish%2C%20and%20birds.%20The%20offspring%20of%20a%20virgin%20birth%20are%20always%20female%20and%20genetically%20very%20similar%20to%20their%20mothers.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20researchers%20first%20sequenced%20the%20genome%20of%20one%20species%20of%20fruit%20fly%2C%20Drosophila%20mercatorum%2C%20which%20has%20the%20ability%20to%20reproduce%20both%20sexually%20and%20through%20parthenogenesis.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20species%20was%20then%20compared%20to%20another%20that%20cannot%20reproduce%20without%20mating%2C%20the%20Drosophila%20melanogaster.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20noting%20which%20genes%20were%20potentially%20responsible%20for%20the%20parthenogenesis%2C%20the%20researchers%20changed%20the%20genetic%20composition%20of%20the%20Drosophila%20melanogaster%2C%20in%20different%20combinations%2C%20to%20match%20that%20of%20the%20Drosophila%20mercatorum.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20the%20end%20of%20a%20six-year%20research%20period%2C%20about%2011%25%20of%20the%20genetically%20engineered%20flies%20were%20able%20to%20successfully%20reproduce%20without%20a%20male%20partner.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20couldn't%20believe%20it%2C%26quot%3B%20Sperling%20told%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fscience%2F2023%2F07%2F28%2Fanimals-asexual-reproduction-genetic-discovery%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%20the%20Washington%20Post%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%26quot%3BWe%20saw%20the%20development%20of%20the%20embryos%2C%20and%20they%20looked%20pretty%20sketchy%2C%20but%20eventually%20they%20kind%20of%20sorted%20out%20and%20developed%20into%20adult%20flies.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EA%20backup%20for%20isolated%20females%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20experiment%20was%20conducted%20on%20fruit%20flies%20because%20they%20are%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencedirect.com%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fabs%2Fpii%2FS0160932713000379%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%20model%20organisms%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20or%20simple%20non-human%20species%20that%20are%20usually%20studied%20to%20better%20understand%20biology.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BFruit%20flies%20are%20incredibly%20special%20because%20they%20are%20basically%20the%20first%20model%20organism%20and%20have%20been%20studied%20for%20over%20100%20years%2C%26quot%3B%20Sperling%20told%20the%20Post.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHannah%20Maude%2C%20a%20researcher%20at%20Imperial%20College%20London%2C%20told%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thetimes.co.uk%2Farticle%2Fscientists-conceive-virgin-birth-in-fruit-flies-9gvg90zln%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EThe%20Times%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20same%20process%20wouldn't%20allow%20humans%20to%20ever%20reproduce%20without%20a%20man.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BOur%20diversity%20protects%20us%3A%20having%20two%20copies%20of%20the%20DNA%20not%20only%20provides%20a%20backup%20for%20harmful%20DNA%20variants%20found%20in%20every%20person%20but%20is%20necessary%20for%20so-called%20imprinted%20regions%2C%20which%20are%20specifically%20active%20from%20the%20maternal%20or%20paternal%20DNA%20copy%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EVirgin%20births%20could%20help%20certain%20species%20and%20act%20as%20a%20%26quot%3Bbackup%26quot%3B%20for%20isolated%20females%2C%20according%20to%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fscience%2F2023%2Fjul%2F28%2Fscientists-induce-virgin-births-in-fruit-flies%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EThe%20Guardian.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20understanding%20parthenogenesis%20could%20help%20with%20the%20control%20of%20insect%20populations%2C%20the%20paper%20notes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20example%2C%20Sperling%20told%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%3Fh%3Dfc94644969ba5f346fdf586c1ddbdf5a3b2befffb37b612db6e11ab323959ef0%26postID%3D64c506c5cf0bcd50abd47207%26site%3Dbi%26u%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.nature.com%252Farticles%252Fd41586-023-02404-z%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%20Nature%2C%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20type%20of%20moth%20in%20the%20UK%20turned%20to%20parthenogenesis%20when%20the%20use%20of%20pesticides%20hindered%20the%20reproductive%20capabilities%20of%20males.%3C%2Fp%